training_organizations.name: Ohio Child Welfare Training Program (OCWTP)
training_organizations.description: A state- and county-funded training system in Ohio that delivers uniform child welfare training through eight regional training centers. The OCWTP, managed in part by the Institute for Human Services (IHS), provides new worker core training, ongoing specialized workshops, and supervisor training for staff from all 88 counties. This public-private collaboration ensures that regardless of county size or resources, all Ohio CPS workers receive high-quality, consistent training.

training_organizations.name: Institute for Human Services (IHS)
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit organization that develops curriculum and coordinates Ohio’s child welfare training. IHS is central to the OCWTP, creating evidence-based training materials and coaching trainers. It also consults nationally, but in Ohio IHS’s role includes managing the state’s standardized online learning system and supporting counties in workforce development, thereby professionalizing the CPS workforce across the state.

training_organizations.name: Northwoods
training_organizations.description: A private company based in Ohio that provides software solutions for child welfare agencies. Many Ohio counties use Northwoods’ Traverse software for electronic document management and mobility, allowing caseworkers to capture case information in the field and access digital case files. Northwoods also provides training and support for these tools:contentReference[oaicite:35]{index=35}, improving efficiency by reducing paperwork and helping Ohio’s caseworkers focus more on families than on filing.

training_organizations.name: Specialized Alternatives for Families and Youth (SAFY)
training_organizations.description: A multi-state nonprofit agency that contracts with county agencies in Ohio to provide therapeutic foster care services. SAFY recruits and licenses foster homes for youth with special behavioral or emotional needs, provides training and support to those foster parents, and offers behavioral health services to stabilize placements. Through SAFY and similar NGOs, Ohio’s county-administered system can expand placement resources and ensure children with higher needs receive appropriate care.
